window.docContents[177].resolve({"/Replete-categories/#Pro-___tale-cohomology--Replete-categories":{"contents":"Let  be a category with limits. By \nwe denote its abelian group objects.\n\n\n\n\n\nWe say  is replete if epimorphisms are stable under sequential\nlimits, i.e., if  is an inverse system in\n such that  is an epimorphism for all\n, then  is an epimorphism for all\n. (Bhatt–Scholze, Definition 3.1.1)\n\nThe following examples are all not needed later, but are useful to gain some\nintuition for repleteness.\n\n* The category of sets is replete (Bhatt–Scholze, Example 3.1.4).* Let  be a field and  a separable closure of . Then the\n  category of sheaves on the small étale site of  is\n  replete if and only if  is a finite extension of \n  (Bhatt–Scholze, Example 3.1.5).* The category of fpqc sheaves, i.e., sheaves on the big fpqc site, is replete\n  (Bhatt–Scholze, Example 3.1.7).\n\nLet  be replete and let\n be a morphism of\ninverse systems in . If  and\n are epimorphisms for each\n, then  is an epimorphism.\n(Bhatt–Scholze, Lemma 3.1.8)\n\nIf  is replete, countable products are exact.\n(Bhatt–Scholze, Proposition 3.1.9)\n\nLet  be replete. If  is an inverse\nsystem in  with epimorphic transition maps, then\n.\n(Bhatt–Scholze, Proposition 3.1.10)\n\n\n\n\n\n","context":"Pro-étale cohomology","header":"3. Replete categories","id":"/Replete-categories/#Pro-___tale-cohomology--Replete-categories"}});